  "solution": {
    "approach": "The factorial of a non‑negative integer N is the product of all integers from 1 to N. Using a do‑while loop we repeatedly multiply a running product by the current value of i, decreasing i each iteration until it reaches 0. For N = 0 the factorial is defined as 1. Because N can be as large as 100, the result does not fit in primitive types, so Java's BigInteger is used. The algorithm runs in O(N) time per test case and uses O(1) extra space besides the result.",
    "timeComplexity": "O(N) per test case, O(T·N) total.",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) extra space (the BigInteger result holds the output).",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n        String line = br.readLine();\n        int T = Integer.parseInt(line.trim());\n        StringBuilder out = new StringBuilder();\n        for (int tc = 0; tc < T; tc++) {\n            int N = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n            BigInteger fact = BigInteger.ONE;\n            int i = N;\n            if (i > 0) {\n                do {\n                    fact = fact.multiply(BigInteger.valueOf(i));\n                    i--;\n                } while (i > 0);\n            }\n            out.append(fact.toString());\n            if (tc + 1 < T) out.append('\\n');\n        }\n        System.out.print(out.toString());\n    }\n}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
  },
